# TypeScript – PandaTrack

## Explicit types

Use explicit types for function parameters and return values for documentation and early error detection.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid
const processUser = (user, options) => {
  return user.name + options.suffix;
};

// ✅ Explicit types
interface ProcessUserOptions {
  suffix: string;
  uppercase?: boolean;
}

const processUser = (user: User, options: ProcessUserOptions): string => {
  const name = options.uppercase ? user.name.toUpperCase() : user.name;
  return name + options.suffix;
};
```

## Prefer unknown over any

Use `unknown` instead of `any` unless there is a strong reason. `any` removes type safety.

## Reusable types

Define interfaces or type aliases for structured data instead of repeating inline object types.

```typescript
// ❌ Repeating object type
const createUser = (data: { name: string; email: string }) => { ... };
const updateUser = (id: string, data: { name: string; email: string }) => { ... };

// ✅ Reusable type
interface UserData {
  name: string;
  email: string;
}
const createUser = (data: UserData) => { ... };
const updateUser = (id: string, data: UserData) => { ... };
```

## Prisma types

Use Prisma-generated types where possible. Extend or compose (e.g. with `Omit` and extra fields) when you need variants instead of redefining models by hand.

Global project types live in `src/types/`.
